objects.name: Operation MacroMaze
objects.description: A cyberespionage campaign targeting government entities in Western and Central Europe using decoy documents mimicking the Spanish government. It utilizes simple tools like VBScripts and headless Microsoft Edge for data exfiltration via Webhook.site.

objects.content:
Sector: Government

Modus operandi:
Spear-phishing with malicious Word documents, XML tracking via INCLUDEPICTURE, living-off-the-land techniques using standard Windows tools and legitimate web services.

objects.name: Canada Goose & Figure Leak

objects.content:

objects.name: ClickFix Variant Using DNS Staging (ModeloRAT)
objects.description:
A new ClickFix variant tricks users into running nslookup commands to retrieve payloads via DNS, leading to the deployment of ModeloRAT.

Analysis:
Attackers are moving away from direct web-based payload delivery to DNS-based signaling to evade proxy/firewall detection. The target shift towards AI Agent frameworks (OpenClaw) represents a new high-value asset for infostealers.

Recommendations:
- Monitor DNS traffic for unusual nslookup queries to external non-standard servers.
- Update Google Chrome and BeyondTrust instances immediately.

objects.content: The threat landscape for February 17, 2026, is dominated by three major trends: the rapid exploitation of critical infrastructure vulnerabilities (BeyondTrust, Ivanti), the emergence of the 'Agentic AI' attack surface, and large-scale ransomware impacts on public services. The discovery and active exploitation of zero-day vulnerabilities in Chrome (CVE-2026-2441) and Apple (CVE-2026-20700) highlight the persistent risk to endpoints. Simultaneously, the OpenClaw framework has become a primary target for infostealers, marking a shift where malware now specifically harvests AI 'souls' and authentication tokens to bypass traditional security controls.
